ts or Culinary Services Degrees in culinary arts or culinary services typically cover food service management, baking and pastry arts, culinary math, nutrition, sanitation topics. Find out about about the curricula of these programs, and learn about career options, job growth and salary info for culinary arts program graduates. View 10 Popular Schools » Show me popular schools Essential Information Individuals who enjoy cooking, baking and creating tasty delights may find culinary arts careers an ideal choice. Formal training programs at the certificate or associate's degree level allow students to create and sample as they learn. Relevant program titles may include, but are not limited, to culinary arts and culinary services. Career Titles Chefs and Head Cooks Pastry Chefs (Bakers) Education Requirements Variable; culinary arts certificate or degree, or apprenticeships Variable; culinary or technical school certificate or degree, or apprenticeships Projected Job Growth (2012-2022) 5%* 6%* Median Annual Salary (May 2013) $42,490* $23,160* Source: *U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics Career Options Individual who complete apprenticeships or formal education in culinary arts have a number of career options. Although they might start out in entry-level positions, they could work to become sous chefs and, later, head chefs or pastry arts specialists. Career Information for Culinary Arts or Culinary Services Professionals Those with degrees in culinary arts or culinary services may find employment in a variety of settings, including leadership positions. Possible employment positions include head cooks, pastry chefs and sous chefs. Head cooks or pastry chefs have many responsibilities beyond devising recipes and creating delicious meals. They may also hire and train other kitchen staff and oversee that everything is operating smoothly in the kitchen. It is also their responsibility to ensure all safety and sanitation codes are met. Career or Salary Outlook for a Culinary Arts Graduate According to the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS), job opportunities for chefs and head cooks are expected to grow at a slower than average rate, with 5% growth between 2012 and 2022 (www.bls.gov); bakers were predicted to only see a 6% growth during that same time. The BLS also reported that head cooks and chefs earned a median annual wage of $42,490 and bakers earned a median salary of $23,160 as of 2013. Educational Requirements Educational requirements for culinary arts or culinary services vary depending on an individual's career aspirations. Students may pursue certificate or degree programs in various areas of culinary arts. Public and private programs are available for those interested in learning wine and beverages, baking and pastry arts or food service management. Course topics include safety and sanitation, culinary math, nutrition, banquet cooking, specialty breads, cultural cuisine and food service technology. In addition to coursework, students complete seminars and receive hands-on learning working in the kitchen. Certifications Certification is a way for individuals to demonstrate their competence in culinary arts or specific areas of culinary services. The American Culinary Federation offers such titles as Certified Culinarian, Certified Master Chef, Personal Certified Chef, Certified Pastry Culinarian and Certified Master Chef. Show me 10 popular schools Related to Career Information for a Degree in Culinary Arts or Culinary Services RelatedRelated Articles Recently UpdatedRecent Articles PopularPopular Articles Culinary Arts Degree Program Video Southern New Hampshire University Video Review Online Courses in Culinary Arts Management Distance Learning Bachelor of Culinary Arts Management College Degree Distance Learning Associate's Degrees in Culinary Arts Management Culinary Arts Degree in Utah Culinary Arts Degree in Cleveland Culinary School: Top Ranked Culinary Arts Program - Philadelphia, PA Students interested in studying cu